            <section class="prose">
              <h2>What is cost per hire?</h2>
              <p>
                Cost per hire is a core recruiting and HR metric that shows how
                much you spend, on average, to hire one new employee. It
                combines all internal and external recruiting expenses over a
                period and divides them by the number of hires.
              </p>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">Cost per hire formula</p>
                <p>Let:</p>
                <ul>
                  <li><strong>IC</strong> = total internal recruiting costs</li>
                  <li><strong>EC</strong> = total external recruiting costs</li>
                  <li>
                    <strong>OC</strong> = onboarding &amp; setup costs
                    (optional)
                  </li>
                  <li><strong>H</strong> = number of hires in the period</li>
                </ul>
                <p>Then:</p>
                <p>
                  \[ \text{Total recruiting cost} = IC + EC + OC \] \[
                  \text{Cost per hire} = \frac{IC + EC + OC}{H} \]
                </p>
              </div>

              <h2>Typical internal vs external recruiting costs</h2>
              <h3>Internal recruiting costs (examples)</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Recruiter salaries and benefits (allocated to hiring activity)
                </li>
                <li>Hiring manager and interviewers’ time cost</li>
                <li>HR and ATS / recruiting software subscriptions</li>
                <li>Employer branding content and careers site maintenance</li>
                <li>Internal referral bonuses</li>
                <li>
                  Office space, equipment, and overhead allocated to recruiting
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>External recruiting costs (examples)</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>Job board postings and sponsored listings</li>
                <li>Agency or headhunter fees</li>
                <li>Background checks and pre-employment screening</li>
                <li>Skills tests and assessments</li>
                <li>Travel and accommodation for candidates</li>
                <li>Relocation packages and signing bonuses</li>
                <li>Career fairs, events, and campus recruiting</li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Onboarding &amp; setup costs (optional but useful)</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>Laptop, phone, and equipment for new hires</li>
                <li>Initial training sessions and onboarding programs</li>
                <li>HR onboarding time and paperwork processing</li>
                <li>Welcome kits, swag, and team events for new joiners</li>
              </ul>

              <h2>How to use this cost per hire calculator</h2>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <strong>Choose your period or cohort.</strong> For example,
                  “Q1 2025 – Sales hires” or “2024 Engineering hires worldwide”.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Enter the number of hires</strong> made in that period
                  or cohort.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Add internal cost items.</strong> Break down recruiter
                  salaries, hiring manager time, HR tools, and other internal
                  expenses.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Add external cost items.</strong> Include job boards,
                  agencies, background checks, travel, relocation, and signing
                  bonuses.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Optionally add onboarding costs</strong> if you want a
                  more complete “cost to get productive”.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Review the totals.</strong> The tool automatically
                  calculates total recruiting cost and average cost per hire.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Copy the summary</strong> to share with finance,
                  leadership, or your HR analytics dashboard.
                </li>
              </ol>

              <h2>Worked example</h2>
              <p>Imagine you hired 8 software engineers in Q2:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Internal costs (recruiter salary allocation, hiring manager
                  time, ATS): <strong>$32,000</strong>
                </li>
                <li>
                  External costs (job boards, agency fees, assessments):
                  <strong>$24,000</strong>
                </li>
                <li>
                  Onboarding costs (equipment, training):
                  <strong>$8,000</strong>
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>Total recruiting cost:</p>
              <p>
                \[ IC + EC + OC = 32{,}000 + 24{,}000 + 8{,}000 = 64{,}000 \]
              </p>
              <p>Cost per hire:</p>
              <p>\[ \text{Cost per hire} = \frac{64{,}000}{8} = 8{,}000 \]</p>
              <p>
                So your average cost per hire for Q2 engineering roles is
                <strong>$8,000</strong>.
              </p>

              <h2>How to interpret and use cost per hire</h2>
              <h3>1. Track trends over time</h3>
              <p>
                Rather than chasing a single benchmark, monitor how your cost
                per hire changes by quarter, by department, and by role type. A
                rising cost per hire may signal:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Increased competition for talent</li>
                <li>Over-reliance on agencies or paid channels</li>
                <li>
                  Inefficient interview processes or too many interview rounds
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>2. Compare channels and strategies</h3>
              <p>
                Use separate cohorts for “agency hires”, “referral hires”, or
                “campus hires” and compare cost per hire and quality of hire.
                This helps you decide where to invest your recruiting budget.
              </p>

              <h3>3. Balance cost with speed and quality</h3>
              <p>
                A very low cost per hire is not always good if it comes with
                long time-to-fill or poor quality of hire. Use cost per hire
                alongside:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Time to fill</strong> – how long it takes to fill a
                  role
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Quality of hire</strong> – performance, retention, and
                  ramp-up time
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Candidate experience</strong> – offer acceptance rate,
                  NPS, or survey scores
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Common pitfalls to avoid</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Inconsistent definitions.</strong> Decide once which
                  costs you include and apply that consistently across periods.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Ignoring internal time cost.</strong> Hiring manager
                  and interviewer time is a real cost, even if it doesn’t appear
                  as a separate invoice.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Mixing very different roles.</strong> Executive hires
                  and entry-level hires have very different cost profiles.
                  Analyze them separately.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Forgetting currency and location differences.</strong>
                  If you recruit globally, calculate cost per hire by region or
                  currency.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>FAQ</h2>
              <h3>What is a good cost per hire?</h3>
              <p>
                Benchmarks vary widely. Many surveys report an average cost per
                hire around <strong>$3,000–$5,000</strong> for typical corporate
                roles in the U.S., but specialized technical or executive roles
                can be much higher. The most useful benchmark is your own
                historical data for similar roles.
              </p>

              <h3>Should I include onboarding in cost per hire?</h3>
              <p>
                If your goal is to understand the <em>total</em> cost to get a
                new employee productive, including onboarding makes sense. If
                you want to compare just the recruiting engine performance, you
                might exclude onboarding and track it separately. This
                calculator lets you do both by toggling onboarding costs on or
                off.
              </p>

              <h3>How can I lower my cost per hire without hurting quality?</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Shift budget from expensive agencies to referrals and direct
                  sourcing.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Standardize and streamline your interview process to reduce
                  wasted time.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Invest in employer branding to improve inbound candidate
                  quality.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Build talent pools so you are not starting from zero for every
                  role.
                </li>
              </ul>
            </section>

